What Reynad describes as a fundamental flaw of Magic actually provides a ton of additional design space 
I wo argue that mana variance is an issue in Magic because sometimes people just do get to play 
People do exacerbate this however 
On the other hand lands in Magic do so much 
Lands can turn into creatures lands can search for creatures lands can copy other lands lands can draw cards some lands do even tap for mana and instead have some very powerful effect 
There an entire subgame built into lands that involves providing you additional versatility usually tapping for two or more colors or having a effect in exchange for some drawback which I find interesting as well 
I think that lands provide an additional benefit in deck design 
You have tons of options when it comes to colors and utility and you have to find the right balance of mana in addition to spells where Hearthstone only mandates that you build an appropriate curve of 
It simply adds another facet of deckbuilding for players to mess with 
To be clear I not trying to bash HS 
I just think that Reynad assessment of lands is missing some pieces 
